Dataset Source¶

The Telco customer churn dataset used in this project was taken from Kaggle. The dataset contains information about a fictional telco company that provided home phone and Internet services to 7043 customers in California. It indicates which customers have left, stayed, or signed up for their service. Multiple important demographics are included for each customer, as well as a Satisfaction Score, Churn Score, and Customer Lifetime Value (CLTV) index.

Dataset Link

Data Dictionary¶

Customer ID: Unique identifier for each customer

Count : Count of the customer

  • 1

Country : Country each customer is located in

  • United States

State : State each customer is located in

  • California

City : City each customer is located in

Zip Code : Postal code associated with each customer's location

Lat Long : Geographic coordinates of each customer's location

Latitude : Latitude value of the location

Longitude : Longitude value of the location

Gender : Gender of the customer

  • Male
  • Female

Senior Citizen : Is the customer a senior citizen?

  • No
  • Yes

Partner : Does the customer have a partner?

  • No
  • Yes

Dependents : Does the customer have dependents?

  • No
  • Yes

Tenure Months : Number of months the customer has been with the company

Phone Service : Does the customer have phone service?

  • No
  • Yes

Multiple Lines : Does the customer have multiple phone lines?

  • No phone service
  • No
  • Yes

Internet Service : Type of internet service opted by the customer

  • DSL
  • Fiber optic
  • No

Online Security : Does the customer have online security?

  • No internet service
  • No
  • Yes

Online Backup : Does the customer have online backup?

  • No internet service
  • No
  • Yes

Device Protection : Does the customer have device protection?

  • No internet service
  • No
  • Yes

Tech Support : Does the customer have tech support?

  • No internet service
  • No
  • Yes

Streaming TV : Does the customer have streaming TV service?

  • No internet service
  • No
  • Yes

Streaming Movies : Does the customer have streaming movie service?

  • No internet service
  • No
  • Yes

Contract : Type of contract the customer has

  • Month-to-month
  • One-year
  • Two-year

Paperless Billing : Has the customer opted for paperless billing?

  • No
  • Yes

Payment Method : Method of payment the customer uses

  • Bank transfer (automatic)
  • Credit card (automatic)
  • Electronic check
  • Mailed check

Monthly Charges : Amount charged to the customer each month

Total Charges : Total amount charged to the customer over their tenure

Churn Label : Whether the customer has churned?

  • No
  • Yes

Churn Value : Binary value for churn label

  • 0 : No
  • 1 : Yes

Churn Score : Percentage probability of churning

CLTV [Customer Lifetime Value] : Average revenue that can be generated from the customer over entire lifetime of their account

Churn Reason : Reason for churning

Source : https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ylchang/telco-customer-churn-1113?rvi=1

In [7]:
# Converting column names
data.columns = [i.lower().replace(' ', '_') for i in data.columns]

Dropping Redundant Columns

  • Customer ID is unique for each of the observation and hence is not a good feature for model building
  • Count, Country and State are having only a single value and hence these features are also not relevant for model building.
  • City is having more than 1000 unique values which may be a problem when encoding categorical variables.
  • Lat Long is an array representing the Latitude and Longitude of the customer. Since these values are already present in the data we can remove this column.
  • Since we are trying to predict the Churn Score all other values that are same as this feature [Churn Label, Churn Value, CLTV, Churn Reason] should be removed.
In [8]:
# Dropping above mentioned columns
data.drop(columns = ["customerid", "count", "country", "state", "city", "lat_long", "churn_label", "churn_value", "cltv", "churn_reason"], inplace = True)

In [90]:
# Graphical Representation of the model
plt.figure(figsize = (15,8))
plt.scatter(x_1_train, y_1_train)
# Regression Line
y_hat = 64.8005 - 0.1971 * x_1_train
fig = plt.plot(x_1_train, y_hat, lw = 4, c = 'red', label = 'Regression Line')
plt.title('Graphical Representation of the model\n', fontsize = 15)
plt.xlabel('Tenure Months')
plt.ylabel('Churn Score')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Observations

  • The correlation between Tenure months and Churn Score is pretty low and hence the spread.

Intercept

  • The intercept value for this model is 64.8005. Since we are trying to predict the churn score, which represents the probability score of churn, the intercept is not a good measure for predicting.
  • Since tenure months cannot be negative, the model suggests that the maximum churn score a customer can have is 64, and the longer the customer is with the company, the more chances there are for him to stay. Logically, this statement is correct, but it is not effective in all cases.
  • If we give a cut-off of 50, then this model will predict that customers will stay for most cases.

Slope

  • Slope of the model tells us that as each month increases, the churn score will decrease by 0.1971 units, starting at 64.
  • This illustrates that as tenure months increase, the chances of customers staying with the company increase.

Model Assessment

In [91]:
model_1_metrics = pd.DataFrame({
    "MSE" : [mean_squared_error(y_1_train, model_1.predict(sm.add_constant(x_1_train))), mean_squared_error(y_1_test, model_1.predict(sm.add_constant(x_1_test)))],
    "RMSE" : [(mean_squared_error(y_1_train, model_1.predict(sm.add_constant(x_1_train))))**0.5, (mean_squared_error(y_1_test, model_1.predict(sm.add_constant(x_1_test))))**0.5],
    "R^2" : [r2_score(y_1_train, model_1.predict(sm.add_constant(x_1_train))), r2_score(y_1_test, model_1.predict(sm.add_constant(x_1_test)))],
    "MAE" : [mean_absolute_error(y_1_train, model_1.predict(sm.add_constant(x_1_train))), mean_absolute_error(y_1_test, model_1.predict(sm.add_constant(x_1_test)))]
}, index = ["Train", "Test"]).T

Observations

  • The model seems to have relatively high errors (MSE, RMSE, MAE) on both training and testing sets.
  • The $R^2$ values are low, indicating that the model doesn't explain much of the variance in the target variable.
  • The metric we choose here is $R^2$.
  • $R^2$ explains the total variance explained by the model. So $R^2$ helps us in understanding whether the variability of the data can be explained by the created model.
  • According to the metric the model is not good enough in predicting churn score. This suggests that we should consider more features to improve the models performance.

Intercept

  • The intercept value for this model is 52.0577. Since we are trying to predict the churn score, which represents the probability score of churn, the intercept for this model is also not a good measure for predicting.
  • The equation tells as that a minimum churn score of 52 will be assigned to all the customers by the model.
  • If we give a cut-off of 50, then this model will predict that all customers will churn.

Slope

  • Slope of the model tells us that as monthly charge increases, the churn score will increase by 0.0986 units, starting at 52.
  • This illustrates that as monthly charges increase, the chances of customers leaving the company increase.

In [107]:
sns.residplot(x_2_train, y_2_train, color = 'red')
plt.title("Residual Plot")
plt.xlabel('Monthly Charges')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')

Observations

  • There is slanting to the right visible in the residual plot.
  • This illustrates that the constant variability is not met.

Conclusion

Based on the above diagnostics and analysis, we can see that relying on a single feature is insufficient to predict the churn score. We should consider more features that influence the response variable in order to build a better model. Adding more features not only enhances the model's accuracy but also helps in understanding customer behavior. Therefore, we have to consider multiple linear regressions.

Model 4

Backward Feature Selection

In [123]:
# Changing column values appropriate for statsmodels formula string

def replacex(col):
    data[col] = [i.replace(' ', '_') for i in data[col]]
    return data[col]

for i in data.dtypes[data.dtypes=='object'].index:
    data[i] = replacex(i)
    
def change():
    z = []
    for i in data['contract']:
        if i == 'Month-to-month':
            z.append(i.replace('-', '_'))
        else:
            z.append(i)
    return z
    
data['contract'] = change()

def change_automatic():
    x = []
    for i in data['payment_method']:
        x.append(i.strip("_(automatic)"))
    return x
    
data['payment_method'] = change_automatic()
In [124]:
# Encoding the data [One-Hot Encoding]
data_encoded = pd.get_dummies(data, drop_first = True)

# Creating intial formula string
formula_string_indep_vars_encoded = ' + '.join(data_encoded.drop(columns = 'churn_score').columns)
formula_string_encoded = 'churn_score ~ ' + formula_string_indep_vars_encoded
In [125]:
# Eliminating features with p-values > 0.05.
telcom_temp_df = data_encoded.copy()

i = 1

removed_columns = []

while i >= 0.05:
    model = sm.formula.ols(formula = formula_string_encoded, data = telcom_temp_df).fit()
    
    try:
        col = model.pvalues[model.pvalues >= 0.05].sort_values(ascending = False).index[0]
    except IndexError:
        break
    
    removed_columns.append(col)
    
    formula_string_encoded = ' + '.join(telcom_temp_df.drop(columns = ['churn_score', col]).columns)
    formula_string_encoded = 'churn_score ~ ' + formula_string_encoded
    
    telcom_temp_df = telcom_temp_df.drop(columns = [col])
    
print(formula_string_encoded)

$ \text{Churn Score} = 39.7306 + 1.226e-05 \times \text{np.power(monthly_charges, 3)} - 2.324e-07 \times \text{np.power(total_charges, 2)} - 5.1239 \times \text{dependents_Yes} + 18.4309 \times \text{phone_service_Yes} + 21.2997 \times \text{multiple_lines_No_phone_service} + 1.0476 \times \text{multiple_lines_Yes} - 2.5416 \times \text{online_security_Yes} - 1.6974 \times \text{device_protection_Yes} - 1.6795 \times \text{tech_support_Yes} - 5.6605 \times \text{contract_One_year} - 5.6557 \times \text{contract_Two_year} + 2.2607 \times \text{paperless_billing_Yes} + 2.5022 \times \text{payment_method_Electronic_check} $

Conclusion

  • The five models, including linear and non-linear approaches, did not result in a significant improvement in predicting churn score.
  • The $R^2$ values across models are relatively low, indicating that the models explain only a small portion of the variance in the target variable.
  • The features considered in these models may not be sufficient to capture the complexities of the underlying patterns, and hence more features may be necessary for a better model building.
